# Container vs Presentational Components

- Presentational components focus on "how it looks".
  - They mainly receive data + callbacks via props.
  - They may include DOM markup and styling, but avoid fetching/mutation logic.
- Container components focus on "how it works".
  - They manage state, side-effects, and behavior (e.g., data loading, mutations).
  - They provide props to presentational components and usually do not own markup/styling themselves.

## Practical guidelines (with hooks)
- If the component is mostly rendering based on props (formatting, lists, layout), prefer a presentational component.
- If the component needs to call APIs, subscribe to state, or wire domain behavior (handlers that depend on app state), prefer a container wrapper.
- Prefer hooks in the container (e.g., `useEffect`, `useState`) and keep the presentational component "pure" for easier testing.
- Avoid over-splitting; use the pattern only when it improves clarity/reuse.

## Sketch example
```tsx
type UsersListProps = {
  users: Array<{ id: string; name: string }>
  onSelect: (id: string) => void
}

function UsersList({ users, onSelect }: UsersListProps) {
  return (
    <ul>
      {users.map((u) => (
        <li key={u.id} onClick={() => onSelect(u.id)}>
          {u.name}
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  )
}

function UsersPage() {
  // container: data loading + behavior
  // (fetch users, define mutation handler, etc.)
  return <UsersList users={[]} onSelect={() => {}} />
}
```

